Here's a concise JavaScript function that checks an array of 5 numbers for a valid prime number and prints it to the console:

```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    if (num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}

function printPrimeNumbers(numbers) {
  if (numbers.length !== 5) {
    console.error("Input array must contain exactly 5 numbers");
    return;
  }

  numbers.forEach((num) => {
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(num);
    }
  });

  if (!numbers.some(isPrime)) {
    console.log("No prime numbers found in the array.");
  }
}

// Example usage:
const inputArray = [11, 15, 7, 20, 13];
printPrimeNumbers(inputArray);
```

In this code, the `isPrime` function checks if a given number is prime. The `printPrimeNumbers` function first validates if the input array contains exactly 5 numbers. It then uses the `forEach` method to iterate over the array and check if each number is prime. If a prime number is found, it is printed to the console. If no prime numbers are found in the array, a corresponding message is printed. The `isPrime` function is optimized by checking only up to the square root of the number.

