Here's a Java solution that checks if a given integer `n` is a power of three without using loops or recursion. This approach utilizes bitwise operations and the property that any power of three has a binary representation with only one '1' bit.

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) return n == 1;

        // The largest power of 3 that can fit in a 32-bit integer is 3^19
        // The binary representation of 3^19 is 1000...01, and for any power of 3,
        // the only '1' bit will be at the position of a power of 2.
        // We can use bitwise operations to check if n is a power of 3.
        // We AND n with all powers of 2 up to 3^19 to see if n has only one '1' bit.
        int bitPosition = 1 << 19;
        while (bitPosition > n) {
            bitPosition >>= 2;
        }

        return (n & bitPosition) != 0 && (n & (bitPosition - 1)) == 0;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // Output: true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // Output: false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // Output: false
    }
